The United States is committed to enhancing allied resilience against various threats at the NATO Warsaw Summit. To support this, the US is providing over $200 million in security assistance and military equipment to help allies improve their national defense capacity, enhance NATO interoperability, and reduce reliance on Russian military equipment. US activities cover military capabilities, civil preparedness, cyber defense, and CBRN defense. The US is also providing specialized assistance to the Baltic States and Poland, including anti-tank capabilities, air defense, ISR systems, and ground-supported air operations equipment and training. Additionally, the US is supporting allied efforts to counter transnational threats such as weapons smuggling and terrorism, and promoting NATO-EU cooperation in addressing these challenges. Various forms of support include operational and training capabilities, information sharing, and equipment upgrades for different countries.